I'm going to call differing headcanons, because I complained about this precise thing on your most recent article.

+bit

-Sorry


I've always seen the Foundation as trying to remain separate from the anomalous, likely as part of the whole  idea. Serpent's Hand may use anomalies to their benefit, the GOC might as well, before shooting them in the back of the head, but for the Foundation, that kind of thing really runs counter to everything they're trying to accomplish and happens only in the direst of circumstances.

The Foundation is Old Man Science, poking his head into the anomalous community and waving his cane, telling the kids to knock off the magic bullshit. They don't employ magicians, they don't use talismans: that's left to the GoIs, that's what separates them from the Foundation. The old adage about advanced tech looking like magic applies, but affecting reality itself seems to me to be the purview of, y'know, reality benders.

Really, I'm more upset about the idea that  runs on a definite, quantifiable set of rules, which it would have to for something like an SRA to function. That a giant arm trapped in a drainage pipe, an endless stairwell home to a malevolent entity and half a cat are all basically the same thing when you get right down to it. That's what this is really about: the Foundation has spent too much time thinking they understand everything, when really, they don't.










