24 Apr 2017 20:29






I think there is some room for improvement, but a +1 nonetheless.

It seems to me that this piece is setting up all the quantified measures on anomalies (Hume readings, SRAs, etc.) as being fundamentally misinterpreted in some way. This may just be because of my viewpoint on the subject - I don't really like the idea that anomalies break the laws of physics simply by being . It also means they're all a result of the same cause, which is simply being too different from limited human understanding of the underpinning functions of the Universe. It suggests that what we know now is complete and perfect, and that simply isn't scientific.

This challenges the assertion, though, and suggests that anomalies can't just be fixed by shooting  at them. I'd like to see more like this, like maybe finding a new skip that completely defies explanation but reads as normal compared to background reality levels. Keep up the good work.







